[Trapping was carried out during the last week of November 2007,
throughout December 2007 and January 2008. It started 3-4 weeks after
the described 3 BTV-1 outbreaks, at the end of the so-called vector
season. No information on virus isolation/identification trials in
the trapped arthropods are included; possibly the (late in season)
timing of the trappings excluded infection in the vectors, anyway.

The mentioned identification of _C. dewulfi_ and _C.chiopterus_ among
the trapped culicoids is interesting: both have been found to be
potential vectors of BTV-8 (see postings 20061024.3042,
20080321.1077).

Noteworthy, on 17 Jan 2008 Spain notified the diagnosis of BTV-8 in
cattle in northern Spain, namely in Solares, Cantabria province,
which had started 9 days earlier; see
<http://www.oie.int/wahid-prod/public.php?page=event_summary&reportid=6689>.

Subscribers are referred to Spain's presentations to EU's SCFCAH
(STANDING COMMITTEE ON THE FOOD CHAIN AND ANIMAL HEALTH, Section
Animal Health and Welfare) meetings of 5-6 Feb 2008 and 4-5 Mar 2008.
The presented maps show that the Guipuzkoa province -- where the
above entomological observations have been undertaken -- are declared
as restriction zones for both BTV-1 and BTV-8. Look for "Bluetongue
in Spain" at
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/committees/regulatory/scfcah/animal_health/presentations_en.htm#18062008>.

As concluded by the authors of the above paper, entomological
findings, indicating the presence of various vector species, such as
_C.imicola_, are important and need to be relayed to regional,
national and international animal health authorities. We fully agree;
earliest possible dissemination of such information deserves to be
encouraged.

The next meeting of SCFCAH is due in Brussels on Mon 30 Jun 2008.
Though bluetongue has not been included in the agenda, it may be
assumed that data on significant developments, in case available,
will be reported. This relates in particular to the appearance of 1st
new BTV-8 disease cases in Europe, which may be anticipated as
temperatures rise (or have already been suspected?!). - Mod.AS]
